{"title":"Session 27: Split Track — Infrastructure Case / Fokker-Planck & Master Equation","markdown":{"headingText":"Session 27: Split Track — Infrastructure Case / Fokker-Planck & Master Equation","headingAttr":{"id":"sec-session-27","classes":[],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n| | |\n|---|---|\n| **Unit** | 5 — Split Track |\n| **Track 1 source** | Class 22 (Infrastructure: The 57% Illusion) |\n| **Track 2 source** | Class 6 (Fokker-Planck Equations) |\n\n---\n\n## Track 1: Infrastructure Case — \"The 57% Illusion\"\n\n### Track 1 Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this session, Track 1 students will be able to:\n\n1. **Apply** GE-LAV to a 20+ year infrastructure asset (longest duration in private markets).\n2. **Identify** why long-duration assets carry the largest accumulated Jensen bias.\n3. **Compute** the \"57% illusion\" — the gap between DCF and GE-LAV for stressed infrastructure positions.\n4. **Translate** GE-LAV findings into pension fund and insurance regulatory language.\n5. **Connect** infrastructure valuation errors to systemic financial stability concerns.\n\n### Track 1 Pre-Class Assignment\n\n- **Read:** Book Chapter 22 case (or Class 22 slides if available)\n- **Optional:** Global Infrastructure Hub report on private infrastructure valuation\n\n### Track 1 In-Class Outline (75 minutes)\n\n| Time | Segment | Format |\n|---|---|---|\n| 0:00–0:10 | Why infrastructure is special: duration + cash flow stability | Lecture |\n| 0:10–0:25 | The \"57% illusion\" decomposed | Lecture |\n| 0:25–0:55 | Lab: value a real infrastructure asset (Indianapolis Toll Road or comparable) | Group work |\n| 0:55–1:15 | Group recommendations + regulatory implications | Presentations |\n\n## Track 2: Fokker-Planck & Master Equation Derivations\n\n### Track 2 Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this session, Track 2 students will be able to:\n\n1. **Derive the Fokker-Planck equation** from the SDE via Chapman-Kolmogorov.\n2. **Prove well-posedness** of the GE-LAV Fokker-Planck (Theorem 14.2).\n3. **State and apply the master equation** for value functions on Wasserstein space (Theorem 15.1).\n4. **Implement** a Fokker-Planck solver for the GE-LAV liquidity state.\n5. **Verify numerical convergence** of the FP solution to the analytical stationary distribution.\n\n### Track 2 Pre-Class Assignment\n\n- **Read:** Book Chapters 14, 15 in full (with proofs)\n- **Pre-read:** Pavliotis, *Stochastic Processes and Applications*, Chapters 4–5; or Risken, *The Fokker-Planck Equation*, Chapter 4\n\n### Track 2 In-Class Outline (75 minutes)\n\n| Time | Segment | Format |\n|---|---|---|\n| 0:00–0:15 | Derivation of FP from Chapman-Kolmogorov | Lecture + board |\n| 0:15–0:35 | Well-posedness (existence + uniqueness): Theorem 14.2 | Lecture |\n| 0:35–0:55 | The master equation on Wasserstein space | Lecture |\n| 0:55–1:10 | Numerical FP solver | Code walkthrough |\n| 1:10–1:15 | Verification: numerical → analytical stationary | Discussion |\n\n### Track 2 Discussion Questions\n\n1. The FP derivation assumes the transition density is Gaussian at small $\\Delta t$. This holds for Itô SDEs with smooth coefficients. What if there are jumps (Lévy processes)? How does the FP change?\n2. The master equation is on Wasserstein space — an infinite-dimensional manifold. Numerically, we discretize $\\mu$ on a grid. What's the discretization error? When does this matter?\n3. The well-posedness theorem requires nondegeneracy ($\\sigma_L > 0$). What happens if $\\sigma_L = 0$ (deterministic OU)? Does the framework break down?\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n[← Session 26](session-26.qmd) | [Schedule](../schedule.qmd) | [Next: Session 28 →](session-28.qmd)\n\n:::{.gelav-product-callout}\n**Run your own scenario:** Apply the FP-coupled GE-LAV® system to a custom infrastructure asset at [liquidityillusion.com](https://liquidityillusion.com).\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"ident